text:
Here's a weird trick. 

a. Pick a 1-digit number (say, 5)
b. Add it to itself three times (5 + 5 + 5 = 15)
c. Multiply by 37 (15 x 37 = ...)
d. Your answer is your starting digit three times in a row! (555)

Qs: 
Does this actually work?
If so, why?
What happens with a 2-digit #?

text: @MatthewOldridge I'm reading a book about it: Kill Switch, by @AJentleson. The book is great, but the history makes for tough reading. The filibuster was primarily used to kill civil rights legislation pre-1970s. Changes in its structure made it easier and less visible to use. Now it's everywhere

text: @MatthewOldridge It's worse. For technical reasons, the senate can delay a vote indefinitely (for "unlimited debate"), unless someone can get 60 votes to stop debate. So effectively, the option to filibuster means that you need 60 votes (of 100) to pass legislation, rather than simple majority

text:
The "pointiness" of an angle of measure x degrees is 
(180-x)/180. 
Eg a straight angle is flat & has 0 pointiness. A small angle is sharp & has pointiness close to 1. The total pointiness of a polygon is the sum of the pointinesses of all its corners. What do you notice? https://t.co/dw11LdFjUD

1. Openers
2. Games
3. Rich tasks

It's a ladder - each step makes the next attainable & appealing.

Openers are easy to start, and involve many of the same moves students need for rich tasks. A natural beginning

text:
@meg_cshaw I think you've got it right. Take the log of both sides and you have

log (10^x) = log (1000), which becomes
x = log (1000)

Sort of tautological, but at least you can plug the right side into a calculator and get log (1000) = 3.

text:
Given a sequence, cross out each term whose position number is a term in the sequence. [eg From 2,4,6,8,.. get 2,6,10,14,...] Repeat. Starting with 2,4,6,8,.. only {2} persists forever. Starting 1,3,5,7,... only {3,7} persist.
Is there a sequence for which inf many terms persist? https://t.co/A3O8YO6Mvq

text: @ablinstein Giving more control to students is'nt an exact science, and can go wrong. But I see this episode as instructive precisely because it looks like it's going to be a catastrophe (teacher kicked off the call!) and ends up a triumph (students took control of class and made it great!)

text: @ablinstein The current moment is one that has us all anxious and out of control. Figuring out ways to let students have more control can be win-win. They're bored, they're motivated, they're looking to connect. Maybe they'd benefit by having more control over zoom class.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:

text: @ablinstein Partly, that it's easy to underestimate what students are capable of. And every time we do something for them that they could do for themselves, we're missing an opportunity for them to step up, to own the experience and take control of the learning.

text: @ablinstein To me, this is a story about a teacher not doing the work they thought they had to do (accidentally, in this case), and the students stepping up and doing it instead. As a result, they have the best class of the year. So what's the moral?

text:
And the magic of it has to do with picking the number of 9s to make a number with some even-sized factors. 

Still some questions, like... does this cover all the cases of this behavior? And, would the algebraic approach have gotten me here too?
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: And the general principle totally makes sense too. It's just about noticing that 1/999..999 = 0.00...001 repeating and then factoring the denominator with the 9s to disguise it a little. Not nearly as bad as I thought it would be.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text:
I'll see if I can make a larger one work. Starting with 999,999,999, I can rewrite it (with help from a computer) as 2997 x 333667.

1/2997 = 0.000333667 repeating
1/333667 = 0.000002997 repeating

It works!
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text:
99 factors as 9 x 11. So are 1/9 and 1/11 partners?

1/9 = 0.1111111...
1/11 = .090909...

Yes - same principle here. It just isn't as elegantly spaced.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text:
I can rewrite 1/27 and 1/37 as 37/999 and 27/999. 

But 1/999 = 0.001 repeating. So multiply that by 37 and 27 and you get 0.037 repeating and 0.027 repeating. Immediately the same for the others! So shouldn't this always work?
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text:
Seems worth looking at what 1/999 is. 
1/999 = 0.001001001 etc.
1/99,999 = 0.0000100001 etc.

That's nice. The number of 9s determines the number of zeros before the 1, which then repeats. Now I think I've got something.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: Wait a minute... multiply the pairs of denominators together and something jumps out: 27 * 37 = 999. 777*1287 = 999,999. And 123 * 813 = 99,999. I'll wager that 831 was a typo for sure! This feels quite important. But why does it work? And why was a case with 9,999 omitted?
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: But 37 and 777 are the two that grab my attention. Why? I know 37 is a factor of 111. And it's a factor of 777 as well. A lot of these numbers are multiples of 3 as well, sometimes with several factors showing up.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: Also interesting is the number of zeroes between the occurrences of the other number. Might be relevant.
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: The thing that jumps out at me right away is that the denominators looks special. 27 & 37, 123 & 831 (there may be a typo in that last one, from glancing at another tweet. Mental note to be careful with that), and 777 & 1287. What's the connection?
bbox_coords: NA NA NA NA NA NA NA NA
name: Dan Finkel
description:
Founder, Math for Love, https://t.co/mWSANzeT3Y.
Cocreator #PrimeClimb, #TinyPolkaDot, #MultByHeart.

text: I've got two ideas for initial approaches: this could be a matter of the factors being special, or it could require algebratizing the behavior and seeing what the algebra tells you. There's deeper stuff that could be involved too, but if it is, I'll have to wait till later.
